04804nmm a2200625Ia 9780520381780DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20222022cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203817807 a10.1525/97805203817802doi  a(DE-B1597)614011  a(OCoLC)1347247472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aHQ281 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.3/62223/eng/202204041 aMitchell, Gregory, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPanics without Borders :bHow Global Sporting Events Drive Myths about Sex Trafficking /cGregory Mitchell. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (318 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Sexual Worlds ;v100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tPreface -- tAcronyms -- tFIFA Men’s World Cup and Summer Olympics Hosts (2000–2028) -- tIntroduction: The Myth of the 40,000 Missing Girls -- t1. Sex Trafficking Discourse as White Supremacy -- t2. Panic at the Gringo -- t3. Fallacious Spectacles and the Celebrification of Sex Trafficking -- t4. Eat—Pray—Labor -- t5. Let Come the Whore Assemblage -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are living in a time of great panic about “sex trafficking”—an idea whose meaning has been expanded beyond any real usefulness by evangelicals, conspiracy theorists, anti-prostitution feminists, and politicians with their own agendas. This is especially visible during events like the FIFA World Cup and the Olympic Games, when claims circulate that as many as 40,000 women and girls will be sex trafficked. Drawing on extensive fieldwork in Brazil as well as interviews with sex workers, policymakers, missionaries, and activists in Russia, Qatar, Japan, the UK, and South Africa, Gregory Mitchell shows that despite baseless statistical claims to the contrary, sex trafficking never increases as a result of these global mega-events—but police violence against sex workers always does. While advocates have long decried this myth, Mitchell follows the discourse across host countries to ask why this panic so easily embeds during these mega-events. What fears animate it? Who profits? He charts the move of sex trafficking into the realm of the spectacular—street protests, awareness-raising campaigns, telenovelas, social media, and celebrity spokespeople—where it then spreads across borders. This trend is dangerous because these events happen in moments of nationalist fervor during which fears of foreigners and migrants are heightened and easily exploited to frightening ends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aHuman traffickingxSocial aspectsy21st century. 0aSportsxSocial aspectsy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Comm 2022 Englishz978311099395008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Education, Psychology, Communication 2022z9783110994186oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076649340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520381780?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520381780423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520381780/original  a978-3-11-076649-3  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  a978-3-11-099389-9  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022